<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: 2 NAMED TO COUNTY TRANSIT COMMISSION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City leaders have appointed two new members to the county's transportation 
panel. 
</P>
<P>
 Moorpark Mayor Paul Lawrason and Ventura resident Roma Armbrust were selected 
by the mayors of the county's 10 cities to serve four-year terms on the Ventura 
County Transportation Commission. 
</P>
<P>
 The seven-member panel of elected officials and citizen representatives meets 
monthly to set transportation policy and dole out about $64 million a year in 
government funding. 
</P>
<P>
 Armbrust replaces Thousand Oaks resident Nancy Grasmehr, whose term expires 
this month. Lawrason replaces Frank Schillo, who served on the panel as a 
Thousand Oaks councilman before he was elected to the Board of Supervisors in 
November. Both Armbrust and Lawrason had served as commission alternates. 
</P>
<P>
 Early next year the Board of Supervisors will select a replacement for 
Supervisor Vicky Howard, who is retiring. Howard was chairwoman of the 
commission. The terms of the other four commissioners expire in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
 According to custom, Supervisor John K. Flynn, who is an alternate on the 
commission, will get first dibs at replacing Howard. The rest of the 
commissioners are Supervisor Susan Lacey, Simi Valley City Councilman Bill 
Davis, Camarillo Councilman David Smith and Michael Wooten, a citizen 
representative from Camarillo appointed by the Board of Supervisors. SARA 
CATANIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
