<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: CALABASAS; AHMANSON LAND TO PLANT 2,000 OAKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MANNING 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Ahmanson Land Co. has launched the latest phase of a long-term program to 
replace hundreds of oak trees cut down to make way for its planned mini-city in 
the hills southeast of Simi Valley, company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Preparations are under way to transplant 2,000 five-foot oaks from a nursery 
to various spots around Ahmanson Ranch, said Stan Roberts of Ag Land Services, 
the company selected to care for the trees. 
</P>
<P>
 The planting was modeled after a pilot program conducted last year in which 
100 trees were planted around the ranch, said Gil Nielsen, senior vice 
president of Ahmanson Land. 
</P>
<P>
 The company last month planted hundreds of acorns in small containers, where 
they will be kept until they mature. According to Nielsen, in about a year, 
they will be transplanted into larger containers, where they will be kept for 
about two more years. 
</P>
<P>
 The 2,000 trees were planted in 1989, in the first phase of the reforestation 
program, Ahmanson officials said. The company plans to plant a total of 4,000 
trees as part of a development agreement that requires it to plant five trees 
for every one destroyed in building the project. 
</P>
<P>
 Ahmanson Land Co. wants to build 3,050 homes, two golf courses and 400,000 
square feet of commercial space in a hilly area southeast of Simi Valley near 
the border of Los Angeles County. Many area residents oppose the project and 
several lawsuits have been filed to block it. In an environmental review of the 
project, it was estimated that 1,300 oak trees would have to be cut down, 
Ahmanson officials said. The company has altered its plans and reduced the 
number to 700. 
</P>
<P>
 Oaks trees seem to be having a difficult time regenerating in many parts of 
Ventura and Los Angeles counties, said Rosi Dagit, conservation biologist for 
the Topanga-Las Virgenes Resource Conservation District. 
</P>
<P>
 Experts aren't sure why, she said, but overgrazing could play a role. It could 
also be, she said, that the natural reseeding process -- through bird 
droppings, for example -- has been stymied. The recent drought, too, may have 
hampered acorn reproduction, she said.  
</P>
<P>
 Dagit said that while she is pleased that Ahmanson Land Co. is planting trees, 
it won't mitigate the negative impact that the Ahmanson Ranch project will have 
on the environment. 
</P>
<P>
 "They are planting trees . . . but they are taking down mature trees," which 
are essential to preserving the area's watershed, she said. "Ten to 20 years 
from now, (the planted trees) will be doing a good job, but in the meantime, 
they are tearing down some beautiful, old trees that have served a purpose for 
so many years." FRANK MANNING 
</P>
</TEXT>
