<DOCNO> LA121594-0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 112694 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
December 15, 1994, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Southeast; Part J; Page 18 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1817 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPORTS; LA MIRADA, MONTEBELLO PLAYERS DOMINATE SOUTHEAST ALL-STARS; FOOTBALL: 
EACH SCHOOL LANDS FIVE PLAYERS ON THE TIMES' 1994 TEAM. SANTA FE AND ST. PAUL 
EACH HAVE THREE SELECTIONS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KIRBY LEE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Call it a tale of two cities with a happy ending. 
</P>
<P>
 La Mirada High repeated as Suburban League champion and Montebello won a share 
of its second consecutive Almont League title. 
</P>
<P>
 La Mirada (13-1) waltzed its way through its first undefeated regular season 
in 10 years. The Matadores outscored their five league opponents, 196-44, 
giving up only one touchdown in their first four league games and reached the 
Southern Section final for the second time in three years. 
</P>
<P>
 The Matadores, who entered the Division VIII playoffs as the top-seeded team 
for the second year in a row, lost to Bloomington, 48-32, Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Montebello (10-2) went undefeated in Almont League play, culminating the 
regular season with a 42-0 victory over previously unbeaten Alhambra. The 
Oilers advanced to the Division III quarterfinals for the second year in a row, 
losing to eventual finalist Ayala. 
</P>
<P>
 La Mirada and Montebello have placed five players each on The Times' 1994 
Southeast All-Star football team. 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Fe (7-4), which won a share of its second consecutive Del Rio League 
title, and St. Paul (7-3), which opened the season with six victories in a row, 
are represented by three players each. Two players from Schurr and La Serna 
were chosen. 
</P>
<P>
 Selections were based on ballots cast by area coaches, all of whom were asked 
to participate, and a poll of Times sportswriters. 
</P>
<P>
 Fred Montiel of Montebello and James Sherman of Whittier were named the back 
and lineman of the year and John Mele of La Mirada was honored as coach of the 
year at an awards brunch Sunday at the Cerritos Sheraton. 
</P>
<P>
 A look at the all-stars: OFFENSE 
</P>
<P>
 Wyatt Boatright, La Mirada, receiver -- The 5-foot-11, 170-pound senior led 
the Matadores with 68 catches for 960 yards. He had nine touchdowns, including 
the game-winning reception in the final minute of La Mirada's 38-35 victory 
over Artesia to secure the Suburban League title in the regular-season finale. 
</P>
<P>
 Guillermo Calderon, Montebello, receiver -- Calderon was an All-Almont League 
selection at receiver and defensive back. The 5-7, 170-pound senior led the 
Oilers with 29 receptions for 655 yards and nine touchdowns. He had 24 tackles, 
19 assists and three sacks on defense. 
</P>
<P>
 Andy George, La Serna, receiver -- George, the Del Rio League receiver of the 
year, had 52 receptions for 812 yards and six touchdowns. The 6-2, 175-pound 
senior has caught more than 100 passes over the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
 Eric Aguilar, El Rancho, lineman -- The Dons' top blocker, the 6-1, 225-pound 
Aguilar had an 80% efficiency rating when El Rancho ran the ball to the 
senior's side. 
</P>
<P>
 Dennis Cash, St. Paul, lineman -- A top-notch blocker, the 6-foot, 243-pound 
senior was selected the All-Del Rey League the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
 Jason Munoz, Montebello, lineman -- The 6-foot, 215-pound senior was a two-way 
player for the Oilers. On defense, he batted down two passes, had 11 solo 
tackles and 43 assists. 
</P>
<P>
 James Sherman, Whittier, lineman -- Nicknamed the "Sherminator" by teammates, 
the 6-4, 290-pound senior tackle was selected to the The Times' Southeast team 
for the second year in a row. The Del Rio League lineman of the year can 
bench-press 430 pounds and has attracted scholarship interest from UCLA, USC, 
Washington, Colorado and Texas.  
</P>
<P>
 David Baruch, California, back -- A two-way player at quarterback and safety, 
Baruch was the only Del Rio League player to be named to the all-league team on 
offense and defense. The 6-2, 192-pound senior is being recruited by UCLA and 
Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
 Geoff Berg, Santa Fe, back -- Berg, the Del Rio League most valuable player, 
was a two-way starter at quarterback and strong safety. The 5-9, 170-pound 
senior completed 75 of 150 passes for 845 yards and 10 touchdowns. On defense, 
he had 68 tackles and three interceptions. Berg also had four fumble 
recoveries, returning two for touchdowns.  
</P>
<P>
 Fred Montiel, Montebello, back -- Montiel made The Times' Southeast team on 
defense last season. The Almont League's most valuable player saw action at 
quarterback, outside linebacker and punter. The 6-1, 185-pound senior completed 
62 of 129 passes for 10 touchdowns. He also rushed for 479 yards in 74 carries 
and eight touchdowns. On defense, he led the Oilers with 39 tackles and 48 
assists. 
</P>
<P>
 Mike Palumbo, La Mirada, back -- The senior quarterback demonstrated great 
efficiency. The 6-0, 180-pound Palumbo completed 172 of 277 passes for 2,145 
yards and 22 touchdowns despite being taken out by the third quarter of most of 
the Matadores' regular-season games. 
</P>
<P>
 Kevin Seto, Schurr, kicker -- The senior punter averaged 43.6 yards a kick. 
The 6-4, 205-pound Seto also played quarterback, where he completed 84 of 164 
passes for 1,296 yards and 10 touchdowns. DEFENSE 
</P>
<P>
 John Dyer, St. Paul, lineman -- The 6-3, 237-pound senior tackle had 42 
tackles and five sacks. The first-team Del Rey League player also knocked down 
five passes and had a fumble recovery. 
</P>
<P>
 Jorge Figueroa, Santa Fe, lineman -- The 5-8, 240-pound Sanchez was the Del 
Rio League defensive lineman of the year. The senior, who bench-presses 400 
pounds, had 70 tackles and 11 sacks. 
</P>
<P>
 Jesus Sanchez, Santa Fe, back -- Sanchez, the Del Rio League most valuable 
defensive back, deflected 12 passes and intercepted three. The 5-8, 160-pound 
senior blocked four extra-point attempts and three punts. 
</P>
<P>
 Donnie Gunritz, La Serna, lineman -- Gunritz is a two-time Times' Southeast 
and Del Rio League first-team selection. The 6-foot, 210-pound senior had 114 
tackles and 73 assists to go along with a blocked punt, five batted passes, 
three sacks and two fumble recoveries.  
</P>
<P>
 Sean Nicolini, La Mirada, lineman -- The 5-11, 180-pound senior had 88 
tackles, four sacks and five fumble recoveries. Nicolini, who blocked three 
punts, blocked a field goal to help preserve La Mirada's 7-6 victory over Norte 
Vista in the Division VIII semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
 Siuta Taufa, La Mirada, lineman -- The 6-1, 220-pound senior had 62 tackles, 
four sacks and three fumble recoveries to anchor the Matadores' line. The 
Suburban League defensive lineman of the year, he blocked two punts in a 
Suburban League game against Norwalk, returning one for a touchdown and the 
other resulting in a safety. 
</P>
<P>
 Oscar Burgueno, Schurr, linebacker -- The 6-2, 235-pound senior was a two-time 
Almont League first-team selection. Burgueno had a hand in 96 tackles, 36 solo 
and 31 assisted. 
</P>
<P>
 Brett Darnell, La Mirada, linebacker -- The 6-1, 225-pound senior was the 
Suburban League defensive back of the year. He had 89 tackles, six sacks, three 
fumble recoveries and two interceptions in helping the Matadores to two 
Division VII playoff appearances in three years. 
</P>
<P>
 Richard Enriquez, Montebello, linebacker -- An Almont League first-team 
selection as a junior and a senior, Enriquez had 25 tackles and 49 assists. The 
5-9, 180-pound Enriquez also had five sacks, four quarterback hurries and broke 
up three passes.  
</P>
<P>
 Art Lucero, St. Paul, linebacker -- An All-Del Rey League first-team 
selection, Lucero was where the action was. The 5-11, 206-pound senior led the 
Swordsmen with 53 tackles and five knocked-down passes. He also intercepted two 
passes and recovered a fumble. 
</P>
<P>
 Adolph Esqueda, Montebello, back -- A two-way player as a defensive back and 
running back, Esqueda had 20 tackles and 24 assists. On offense, the 5-8, 
185-pound senior led the team in scoring with 66 points. Esqueda rushed for 678 
yards in 108 carries, an average of 6.3 yards, and 10 touchdowns. He also 
caught 19 passes for 226 yards and a score. 
</P>
<P>
 Jesus Sanchez, Santa Fe, back -- The 5-8, 160-pound senior, who was named the 
Del Rio League defensive back of the year, blocked four extra-point attempts, 
three punts and a field goal. He also had three interceptions and deflected 12 
passes. SECOND TEAM OFFENSE 
</P>
<P>
 Receivers -- Kenyon Rambo, Long Beach Poly; Eric Grace, Lakewood. 
</P>
<P>
 Linemen -- Greg Edelin, Long Beach Jordan; Kevin Bloodworth, Artesia; Joe 
Salcido, St. Anthony; Gerardo Arredondo, Long Beach Poly; Ernesto Jacobo, 
Paramount. 
</P>
<P>
 Backs -- Ortege Jenkins, Long Beach Jordan; Jua Jackson, Artesia; Ahmad 
Jackson, Long Beach Jordan; Ryan Williams, St. John Bosco. 
</P>
<P>
 Kicker -- Sam Vance, Bellflower. SECOND TEAM DEEFENSE 
</P>
<P>
 Linemen -- Terrell Sutton, Dominguez; Freddy Alvarado, Jordan; Bryan Penn, 
Mayfair. 
</P>
<P>
 Linebackers -- Vince Vigil, St. John Bosco; Trevor Hefner, Valley Christian; 
Rene Pena, Paramount; Trayton Bullard, Dominguez; Etieni Valele, Norwalk. 
</P>
<P>
 Backs -- Albert Perez, Paramount; Cameron Johnson, St. Anthony; Don Lonon, 
Long Beach Poly. 1994 Prep Football All-Stars 
</P>
